sium and low sodium concentrations","High chloride and low protein concentrations","High sodium and low potassium concentrations"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe distribution of \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh potassium and low sodium concentration\u003C/strong\u003E is maintained by the sodium-potassium ATPase pump, which actively transports sodium out of cells while bringing potassium in.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh bicarbonate and low phosphate concentrations\u003C/strong\u003E - Phosphate is found in higher concentrations within cells and is an important component of many intracellular molecules.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh calcium and low magnesium concentrations\u003C/strong\u003E - Intracellular calcium is maintained at very low concentrations through active transport, while magnesium levels are higher intracellularly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh chloride and low protein concentrations\u003C/strong\u003E - Proteins serve as the primary intracellular anions, while chloride is predominantly found in the extracellular space.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh sodium and low potassium concentrations\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the composition of extracellular fluid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENormal intracellular concentrations include potassium (140 mmol/L), sodium (10 mmol/L), and magnesium (15 mmol/L). The main anions are proteins and phosphate-containing compounds.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Intracellular fluid contains high concentrations of potassium and low concentrations of sodium due to the sodium-potassium ATPase pump.","Magnesium and phosphate are found in higher concentrations inside cells compared to extracellular fluid.","The main intracellular anion is protein, followed by phosphate."],"references":["Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019.","Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61404"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17661"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61404"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T08:30:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T12:48:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10375"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75891"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4933","lin